text = "
Mara and her mother Emunah,
are in a small clearing within The
Hanged Garden. It is 4:00 in morning,
and the full moon is just barely visible,
its light breaching through the misty
tree line. 

Mara: Why do we always have to do this
early in the morning? I’m barely even awake,
and I’m sure the spirits are too.

Emunah: The spirits are restless, Mara, and
the rest of the world’s lack of faith in them
is not helping that. This is the least we can
do for them – for what they have done for us. 

	  Now, kindly get that spirit stone back
to where it belongs. The moon is setting soon,
and we won’t be able to perform the ritual.

Mara inspects the spirit stone, noticing that it
has a full moon carved on one side. She
pushes it towards a circle of stones, each
marked with a phase of the moon, making
sure that her stone’s carving is facing towards
the others. The ritual begins shortly after, as
Emunah stands outside the circle and invokes
the moon. As the fading moonlight bathes the
clearing, the stones glow, before unleashing a
bright space pulse that spreads through the forest.

After Emunah finishes the ritual at the break of
dawn, she and Mara prepare to leave when
they hear loud noises coming from the edge of
the forest. Emunah wants to investigate the
disturbance, to which Mara insists on coming
with her.

Mara: Looks like the spirits are angry. Did we do
something wrong?

Emunah: That was not the work of a spirit. I
Have heard that sound before, and it only
means trouble.

Mara: Why? What is it? 

Emunah: Listen to me Mara, you need to go
home now and start preparing the things that
we need to invoke a spirit. I will come home
in the morning – and do not leave the house.

Mara: You still haven’t answered my questions. 
I’m coming with you, whether you like it or not.

Emunah: I do not like it, and you will not. Go
home. Prepare. Lock up. 
Please, Mara. Go. Now. 

Mara hears the concern in her mother’s voice
and sees the fear in her eyes. She wants to know
what’s going on, but decides to listen to her,
running in the opposite direction, towards their
home. As she does, she trips on one of the spirit
stones, displacing the one carved with a lunar eclipse.
She hastily puts it back, and runs home – the loud
noises reverberating from behind her.

"
