text = "
Mara manages to return home as the dawn
breaks. She opens the door and instantly goes
to her mother’s room, hurriedly rummaging
through the cabinets, looking for the things
that she needs to invoke a spirit.
Mara: Good spirits, good spirits.
Think Mara, think!

…

Aha! The Elder Nightwood Branch and
a Hallowed Hyacinth.

Mara finds The Elder Nightwood Branch and
Hallowed Hyacinth in her mother’s cabinets.
She takes them out, and runs to their living
room, placing the items on the altar just as
her mother had instructed her. She waits
for her until 9:00 in the morning, and when
she still does not return, Mara performs
the ritual herself.

Mara: I invoke thy names, Children of The
Hanged Garden… I-I, Mara, your servant, desire
an audience with thee. Hear my plea,
and come in peace.

The wind stills, and Mara waits, and waits.
She curls into the fetal position as a sense of
both fear and hopelessness wash over her.

Suddenly, the winds pick up again and Mara
feels an unnaturally cold gust pass through her.
Returning to the kneeling position, she calls to
the spirit she knows she has just summoned,
a sense of pride, tinged with hope in her voice.

Mara: W-who are… I mean, O, Child of The
Hanged Garden, my many thanks to thee.

Hutik: I am Hutik, spirit of whispers, and
I have heard thy prayer, Mara.

Mara: My mother Enumah, she-

Hutik: Has not returned home, and thou art
worried for her safety?

Mara: Y-yes, can… Canst thou assist me, O spirit
of whispers?

Hutik: That and many more, Mara.
Now, make haste, for we shall depart. We shan’t
waste any time.

Mara: I-I have to get something first.

Mara runs into her room, grabbing her cloak
from her bed, and rushes out of the house. The
cloak was old, it was her mother’s from when
she was a girl her age and had been used as a
ceremonial garb. Mara on the other hand has made
a habit of neglecting it, finding it too
uncomfortable and necessary. However, now that
her mother is missing, she feels as though she
needs to bring and wear it - for her.

Hutik: I had noticed that thou were not wearing
the ceremonial garb when thou had
summoned me. Why?

Mara: I don- I do not usually wear it. It is too
big for me, and besides, I believe that there is
so much more to faith than what you wear.

Hutik: Interesting…

With Hutik as her guide, Mara leaves the safety
of her house and ventures into depths of The
Hanged Garden, jumping over rocks and crawling
under logs along the way.

"
