text = "
(Above Ground Path)

Mara stumbles through the dense woodland.
She has lived in The Hanged Garden all her life,
but has never gone this deep into it before. She
climbs a fallen tree, arriving on top of a small
hill where she notices a rock, poking out of the
thick shrubbery and approaches it, and as she
does, she realizes that it is carved, much like the
ones that her mother used the night before.
However, instead of the phases of the moon this
one is carved with the sun. Intrigue washes over
her face, which Hutik immediately notices.

Hutik: Thy ancestors once lived deep in The Hanged
Garden. They were one with both the spirits and
the nature around them. However –

Mara: Some began to lose faith in the spirits and
left the forest. They- my apologies.

Hutik: Go on, I am interested to see how much
thou truly knows about thy history.

Mara: Th-they began building settlements, towns,
and then cities, which drew more and more
people out of The Hanged Garden, until only a
faithful few remained. And now, it is only my
m-mother and I.

Hutik: Indeed, now it is only thy mother and
thee, fulfilling thy purpose to The Hanged Garden.
A purpose that many have attempted to flee from,
yet always find themselves serving.

(Underground Path – Optional / Hidden Location)

Mara begins climbing a fallen tree that serves as
a bridge between the forest floor and a small
hill that looms over her. However, unbeknownst
to both her and Hutik, the tree has been
weathered and breaks as she is climbing it. Mara
falls into a small underground cavern, with its
walls covered by plant root and bone. She
stumbles around in the dark until her hand grazes
a hard surface, which slowly begins to hum and
emit a faint light.

Mara hears Hutik stifle a gasp, which surprises
her, but as her eyes adjust to the growing
brightness, she realizes why. The light reveals a
partially covered stone mural, with the visible parts
depicting The Elder Nightwood and two vaguely
humanoid figures. Mara notes that one figure seems
to be emerging from the ground like a plant, while the
other one has a large chimaeric body. Both of their
faces however are hidden beneath large and
immovable plant roots.

Mara: W-who… What is all of this?

Mara asks Hutik a question but he remains silent, 
until Mara, ever-stubborn, and seeming to forget
that she is talking to a spirit, asks him again, this
time raising her voice. Hutik, uncharacteristically
answers with hesitation.

Mara: What. Is. All of this?
W-who are those in-
My sincerest apologies, O Child of The
Hanged Garden. I-

Hutik: I accept thy apology, Mara. But thou must
remember that there are myriad spirits that
inhabit The Hanged Garden, some older than I.

I-I am spirit of much youth, and many events
have transpired long before I awoke. I do not know
what the mural means, and I doubt that it will
be of much help in locating thy matron.

Mara: B- I understand, O spirit.

Mara knows that Hutik is hiding something from
her, especially regarding the stone mural and its
content. However, she also knows that antagonizing,
or worse, angering, the only spirit who answered her
prayer only hurts her chances of finding her mother.

The thought of her mother, and Hutik’s ominous tone
are enough to make Mara continue in silence.  As the
pair continue to trudge through the forest Mara finds
herself bouncing off of Ghast Caps, and pushing
branches, logs, and rocks out of her path.

Eventually, they stumble into a clearing, and the
light of sun, now at its zenith bathes it in blinding
and hot light. Mara looks around the clearing, until
Hutik points her to a patch of suspiciously fresh dirt.
A sense of dread washes over Mara, and she
hesitatingly approaches it.  She kneels down, and claws
at the ground, scooping up clumps of dirt until she
unearths her mother’s dead body, noticing that the
left side of her head had been cracked open.

Grabbing onto her mother’s cloak, Mara curls into
the fetal position and breaks down, crying. Hutik
stays silent during all of this, seemingly apathetic to
Mara’s grief. After she spends some time crying,
Mara stops, and slowly begins to stand up, wiping
the tears off her face. Mara looks at her mother’s
corpse forlornly, not knowing what to do as she has
never seen a, and never been required to perform
a ritual for death.

Mara: I- I’m so sorry mother. I couldn’t save you. If
only you- if only I went you, maybe this wouldn’t
have happened.
I- I failed you. I’m so sorry.

Hutik continues to stay silent, observing Mara
and her actions, as she begins to scour the
clearing and the nearby woods,
clearly looking for something.

Mara: Mother’s love… What was it again?
Think, Mara.
Carmine Carnation, that’s it!

Mara looks around and spots a field of Carmine
Carnations, quickly rushing to, and picking one
of the flowers. Shen then slowly approaches her
mother’s corpse, and lays the Carmine Carnation
on her left breast, before uttering a simple prayer
which she has come up with on the stop.

Mara: Enumah, my mother. I thank you for
everything, may your soul find peace. M-

Hutik: Enumah, Mara’s matron, I thank thee for
thy service.
May thy soul find peace, and serve its purpose in death.

As the pair finish their ritualistic elegy the Carmin
 Carnation begins to grow, wrapping Enumah’s
corpse in its petals before exploding. Mara looks on
in awe as The Hanged Garden takes its course,
granting her mother peace. However, Mara knows
that she herself will remain restless as long as her
questions remain unanswered; “What was the noise
that they heard coming from the edge of the forest?”,
“Why was her mother so concerned?”, and
“Did it have anything to do with her death?”.

Suddenly, Mara sees multiple impressions in the dirt
which she, in her grief, had not noticed before. Her
eyes follow the direction that they seem to have come
from and returned to, and both anger and resolve
find their way into her hollowed heart.

